history as Montage — Invisible Legs and the Soil of the Local

by Jiseung Shin

A few days from now, I plan to watch a film titled Perugino, Eternal Renaissance. Strangely, I feel an unusual anticipation toward it. What kind of perspective could possibly frame Perugino? As a creator, I am deeply curious.

It would mean something significant if the film managed to discover a gaze entirely different from works such as The Agony and the Ecstasy or Michelangelo: Infinity.

For me, the Sistine Chapel had always belonged to Michelangelo alone — The Creation of Adam, The Last Judgment. Then suddenly, Perugino appeared like an unexpected crack within that monumental image.

And through that crack, an old memory from a film set returned to me.

The story we were shooting was simple enough: an ordinary housewife is accidentally discovered by an advertising agency while shopping because of her beautiful legs, and her previously mundane life slowly unravels into confusion.

But what happened on the set was more complicated than the story itself.

Once the female lead finished filming, the director would casually say, “You’re done for today, you can head home,” then exchange a glance with me.

After she left, I would check the skirt and shoes she had been wearing, then continue filming with another actress. Most of the remaining shots were close-ups of legs.

The face, dialogue, and acting had already been completed by the lead actress. But the legs belonged to a different, unknown performer whose body was considered more beautiful.

In the end, two people existed within a single scene.

The face belonged to one woman.
The legs belonged to another.

The production staff kept this hidden because they feared the lead actress would feel hurt if she found out. Eventually the truth was exposed, and she expressed quiet disappointment toward the director.

It was a story about a woman admired for her beautiful legs, yet in reality someone else’s legs replaced her own.

Even I remember feeling a strange confusion. What thoughts passed through the minds of the lead actress and the anonymous body double?

The protagonist had unknowingly become a kind of Frankenstein — a body stitched together from different people beneath a single face. And I was merely the witness who saw the seams.

Whenever I remember that moment, I feel an unsettling overlap with today’s AI-generated images and synthetic montage.

Perhaps that old memory resurfaced now because of the name “Perugino.”

For a long time, I remembered history through only a few names: Michelangelo, the Medici family, the Pope, the Sistine Chapel. Those names alone seemed to form the face of the Renaissance itself.

But encountering Perugino again allowed me to glimpse another world hidden behind that face.

Perugino reportedly spent his childhood in poverty in the small Umbrian city of Perugia. As a boy, he wandered into a local painter’s workshop and dreamed of becoming an artist himself.

That painter was likely no famous master. Few works may even remain under his name. Yet the fact that such an ordinary figure planted artistic desire inside a child feels profoundly important.

The beginning of an artistic era did not emerge solely from palaces or grand cities, but from local workshops.

Looking more closely, I realized that Renaissance Italy was sustained by regional networks of studios and craftsmen. Each workshop accumulated techniques while sharing local aesthetics, landscapes, and styles with neighboring regions. Artists moved from city to city following the patronage of churches, popes, and local powers, much like wandering scholars during China’s Spring and Autumn period.

That journey eventually brought Perugino to Rome.

Summoned by the Pope, he painted frescoes within the Sistine Chapel, and within his workshop many disciples were trained. Raphael himself grew inside that environment.

Yet the final chapter of Perugino’s life unfolded differently.

Eventually, he returned home.

At the age of seventy-eight, he died while painting altar frescoes for a church in his hometown.

Meanwhile, the age of art was already shifting around him.

Michelangelo reportedly dismissed Perugino as “a man ignorant of art,” and Perugino sued him for defamation. As papal power changed, the altar wall of the Sistine Chapel was redesigned. Perugino’s fresco — The Assumption of the Virgin — was entirely erased, replaced by Michelangelo’s The Last Judgment.

Had Perugino lived to witness it fully, the humiliation must have been devastating.

Yet now, when I think of the Sistine Chapel, only The Last Judgment rises immediately in my mind. I had never even possessed the ability to imagine what existed beneath it before.

Scenes often appear to emerge suddenly, but beneath them lie long histories of accumulation.

Before Kim Hong-do, there were Yun Du-seo’s women gathering herbs, and countless other painters of everyday life.

It is much like that film set where a woman’s face and another woman’s legs were edited together into a seamless illusion.

Audiences remember the actress’s face. They never ask whose legs appeared beneath it.

Because those legs become invisible labor. Invisible existence.

The history of the Renaissance was edited in much the same way.

Most people remember Michelangelo, not Perugino.

That too is a form of montage.

Yet we easily forget the countless local workshops, techniques, collaborations, and systems of patronage that made such monumental figures possible.

History edits away many things in order to produce a unified narrative.

And so the Renaissance appears to belong to Michelangelo alone, while beneath that singular image rested the accumulated time of Perugino and countless unnamed painters.

This week, I intend to watch that film.

I still do not know whether it will simply present another story of genius, or whether it might finally reveal the owner of those elegant invisible legs hidden beneath history’s polished face.

If it remains merely a textbook biography of Perugino, I will probably leave disappointed.

What seems certain, however, is that the fate of artists has always been shaped by political power, religious authority, and local patrons. That reality has perhaps not changed very much even now.

The history I learned was itself a montage — different faces and legs stitched together until two people appeared as one.

Perhaps that is also the essence of art itself: a palimpsest, where erased histories continue to haunt the surface, and a kind of kintsugi, where fractures and wounds are held together with gold rather than hidden away.
